Refer the below document for setting up KIND clusters for peering and setting peering between them before we proceed with usage of exported services in peering setup:-
https://github.com/abhineet-1987/Abhineet/blob/main/Consul/Kubernetes/KIND/PodToPodCommunication-MultiCluster
https://github.com/abhineet-1987/Abhineet/tree/main/Consul/Peering/Kubernetes/control-plane-peering

Steps:-
Deploy static-client app static-client.yaml in cluster-01. "kubectl appy -f static-client.yaml"
Deploy static-server app static-server.yaml in cluster-02. "kubectl appy -f static-server.yaml"
Deploy ExportedServices CRD into cluster-02. "kubectl appy -f exported.yaml"
Deploy ServiceIntentions CRD into cluster-02 if ACLs are enabled else not required. "kubectl appy -f intentions.yaml"

Validation:-
kubectl debug -it static-client-7cbc46f79-td5k8 --image=nicolaka/netshoot -- sh
curl localhost:1234
"hello world from exported service"

Note: Even though you use below annotation in static-client app, you have to create ExportedServices CRD in cluster-02 else you'll get error "url: (56) Recv failure: Connection reset by peer" when you run "curl localhost:1234" on static-client app pod
annotations:
        consul.hashicorp.com/connect-service-upstreams: "static-server.svc.cluster-02.peer:1234"

You can run "kubectl port-forward svc/consul-server 8501:8501" on other terminal and then open browser and open the url "https://127.0.0.1:8501" to view Consul UI.
If you need to run CLI commands then run below:-
export CONSUL_HTTP_ADDR=https://127.0.0.1:8501
export CONSUL_HTTP_SSL_VERIFY=false

If ACL deployed then:
kubectl get secret consul-bootstrap-acl-token -o yaml
echo <token-copied-from-above> | base64 -d
export CONSUL_HTTP_TOKEN=xxxxxxxxxxxx
